Based on the AAR foregoing, we recommended to the management the following actions:
1)Review the LGU's AIP preparation process to ensure that the PPAs and their allocated funds are realistic and consistent with the available resources, taking into account the estimated revenue, expenditure, and funding sources;
2)Evaluate the LGU's budgeting process to ensure that the Annual Budget is aligned with the AIP and that there are clear guidelines and procedures for monitoring and adjusting the appropriations as needed;
3)Conduct a comprehensive analysis of the LGU's revenue projections, taking into account historical trends, economic conditions, and other relevant factors, to ensure that they are reliable and realistic;
4)Verify the LGU's compliance with applicable laws, regulations, and accounting standards, including the Local Government Code, the DILG CDP Guidelines, DILG-NEDA-DBM-DOF JMCs, and other relevant guidelines and policies; and,
5)Provide guidance and training to LGU personnel involved in the planning and budgeting process to enhance their understanding of the importance of the linkage between the plan and budget, the principles of good governance, and the best practices in financial management.

We recommend the management to direct the ensuing personnels the following course of actions:
To the Municipal Accountant:
1) Constantly review and monitor the system-generated depreciation schedule for the correctness of the data using the underlying provisions and basis of computation provided by Section 262 of GAM for LGU Vol 1, PAG 3 for IPSAS 17, and generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP);
2) Create a report to the Government Accounting Sector (GAS) of the Commission on Audit (COA) or any person in charge of the e-NGAS system regarding any glitches or flaws on the implementation of the said application in order to appropriately log the said glitches and correct or fix the same;
3) Exert effort to create a manual computation on the depreciation of the PPEs as a guide for the correct figures and adjust accordingly any errors in contrary to the underlying guidelines;
4) Consider designating a personnel who has knowledge in computer systems for real-time troubleshooting of the minor glitches of the accounting system;
5) Ensure that all PPEs subject for depreciation have been provided with a depreciation expense and that all data necessary have been appropriately logged in, such as the acquisition cost in compliance with IPSAS 17 and other pertinent accounting regulations, and to recompute or create a new lapsing schedule for the depreciation following the adjusted details on useful life and acquisition cost;
6) Install an internal control with regards to counter-checking the details logged in the system and ensure that complete and accurate data have been provided;
7) Recompute the depreciation based on the change in accounting estimate due to the alteration of the residual value as stipulated in the GAM for LGU Vol. 1 and apply the same in prospective application on the period following the audit year;
8) Prepare the appropriate journal entries and other accounting records to correct the depreciation and effect the necessary adjustments in order to rectify the errors and present the asset accounts to their proper carrying amount; and,
9) Exert effort to properly identify and verify the existence of the PPEs that have already lapsed in useful life in order to confirm its existence and reassess any estimates provided for such accounts.

We recommend the management to direct the BAC the following course of actions:
1) Communicate with the GPPB and inquire regarding any error on the posting requirements and inquire for the reason why the submitted entries were not posted;
2) Exert effort to coordinate with the end-users or implementing departments after the approval of the appropriation ordinance for any changes in the APP and update and/or revise the same;
3) Ensure that the details in the APP, particularly the ABC, is consistent with appropriations for the project authorized in the GAA, continuing, and automatic appropriations, the corporate budget, and the appropriations ordinance, as the case may be;
4) Ensure that any updated reports or revised reports are submitted to the Commission on Audit at least 5 days after the change has been reflected and approved for auditorial review;
5) Prepare the project requirements and attach them with the contracts and DVs submitted in order to support the validity, verifiability, and completeness of the claims; and,
6) Properly check the completeness of the documentary requirements submitted by each supplier/contractor in each contract/transaction undertaken with the agency.

We recommend the Local Chief Executive to direct the BAC Secretary to:
1) Submit all unsubmitted contracts, all in original form, from period January to December 31, 2020;
2) Strictly adhere to the requirements set forth in COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009, specifically that of submitting the required documents within the reglementary period;
3) Secure original or authenticated copies as an attachment for the disbursement vouchers and other than the documents prepared in compliance with the abovementioned regulations; and
4) Determine any unsubmitted contracts not included in the data taken from PhilGEPS and submit required documents for such contracts to the Commission on Audit.

We recommend the Local Chief Executive Officer, as head of the agency to:
1.Require the Accountant and the Property Officer to maintain complete property and equipment ledger cards as required under Sec. 43 of NGAS, Volume I & Sec C. 3, Chapter V of the Manual on Property Custodianship;
2.Require the Inventory Committee to conduct year-end physical inventory on Property, Plant & Equipment, including the Construction-in-Progress, Road Networks and completed Infrastructure Projects and submit it to the Accounting for reconciliation of balances as a requirement to Sec 57 of the NGAS Manual, Volume I to ensure correctness and reliability of the PPE account balances;
3.Require the Accountant and the General Services Officer to analyze the discrepancy between the balances in the books and per physical count of the PPE Accounts and to make the necessary adjustments in their records to take up the noted differences affecting current year’s transactions. Also, locate the missing/unreconciled properties; and,
4.Require the GSO to annually provide a copy of the reconciled RCPPE to the COA, not later than the 31st day of January of ensuing year, showing therein the proper classification of PPE as shown in PPSAS accounts. Also, prepare Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties.

